@node Introduction "Introduction to the Everyday-Organiser."

Everyday Organiser (EO) consists of three main programs designed to help you manage your personal day-to-day activities. You can store friends addresses while keep up-to-date on events such as birthdays and appointments etc. It acts slightly differently to some other systems but is easy to use. 

· The functioning of the Organiser system is split up into different programs so you may choose which ones to use, and how to use them.

· The EO 'system' features a powerful and flexible notification structure that a lot of Personal Organisers fail to provide. 

· The main programs have been designed with ARexx in mind. A number of practical scripts are provided to give examples on how to solve those 'difficult situations'.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

The programs included with EO are:

@{b}On-Time@{ub}...: A personal event and task manager.

@{b}Alarmist@{ub}..: A daily alarm management program that can be used on its own but is
            best used in conjunction with On-Time.

@{b}Locate@{ub}....: Yet another contestant in the wonderful world of Address Management
            programs ;-).

There are four extra utility programs included:

@{b}TimePrefs@{ub}.: MUI replacement for the Workbench Time preferences program that
            directly supports Alarmist and On-Time.

@{b}Talk@{ub}......: Replacement for CLI 'Say' command. Has quite a lot more features!

@{b}Sam@{ub}.......: Small & simple yet useful CLI sound-datatype player.

@{b}Coder@{ub}.....: Small CLI program to encrypt files.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

@{b}HOW THE SYSTEM WORKS@{ub}

The program Alarmist needs to be running at all times because it performs the central notification mechanism. On-Time need only be run when it is needed, although it can sometimes be useful to have in your WBStartup if you can afford the extra memory.

On startup, Alarmist will display reminders for the current day and warn you of different events as they occur throughout the day. When you want to enter in a new event for a later date, eg. a birthday or appointment, you use On-Time. Alarmist takes note of when you change events in On-Time and updates itself.

The program Locate can be loaded at anytime (or remain in memory) to provide a simple method of storing addresses or other simple lists. You may load multiple copies of Locate at one time whereas only single copies of Alarmist and On-Time can be run at once.

Talk, Sam and Coder are small utility programs to compliment the system.

I hope that Everyday Organiser does all that you need and is fun to use,

	Mathew Wilson - April 1997, Adelaide, South Australia.
@endnode

@node Giftware "EO is Giftware"

	@{b}EVERYDAY ORGANISER IS GIFTWARE@{UB}

As of release 2.30, Everyday Organiser is classified as Giftware (see @{"License Agreement and Disclaimer" link License}). 

EO has been in development since 1995, and was first released in February 1996. A huge amount of time and work has gone into the development of the EO programs, including much re-writing and optimisation over this period.

Previous to release 2.30, EO was classified as Freeware, as I was keen to get an organiser system on the Amiga that followed my philosophy and used the unique and powerful facilities of the Amiga. In release 2.20 I documented that it would be the very last version of EO on the Amiga. At that point in time I found myself looking back and wondering whether all that work had been worth it. Because of the inadequacies of other Operating Systems and the number of emails I received, I have returned to Amiga development to 'see what happens'.

My original motivation for EO was personal (and still is), but now I realise that others are using this system to help organise there lives. While I would *never* say that EO is the best and it does everything, I would hope that by now, people are finding it useful in their everyday lives.

To help encourage me to continue development of EO on the Amiga it is suggested that you send me a donatation. I desperately need a new Amiga, and any small amount of money will be of some use. There are people out there using EO on Amigas that make my current one look rather humorous :)

I was thinking of re-classifying EO as Shareware but that brings more problems than I feel is worth at this time. I do not want the classification of this software package to hinder anyone from sending me email. If you feel that EO doesn't deserve any financial contribution then this doesn't mean I don't want to hear from you!

There are two preferred ways of sending me money:

1. @{b}Electronic Transfer@{ub}

Have your bank electronically credit my account using the following details:

	Commonwealth Bank of Australia
	Mitcham   South Australia
	065140 10012820

2. @{b}Bank Draft Cheque@{ub}

Have a Bank Draft Cheque drawn out to me:

	Mathew Philip Wilson


The first method is usually the more expensive, so you might prefer the second method.

My postal address is:

	Box 6022, Halifax Street
