@node Requirements "Requirements"

	@{b}Things You Will Need@{ub}
	
Because the Everyday Organiser systems is split in to component programs, each separate program may require different external resources, eg. libraries. Sometimes these resources are not always needed but are recommended for correct operation. Apart from what is included with the EO archive, you will need the following external resources:

· @{"MUI" link AboutMUI} 3.8 (Stefan Stuntz) - mui38usr.lha
· wbstart.library 2.2 (Stephan Becker) - WBStart.lha
· ScreenNotify.library (Stephan Becker) - SNotify.lha
· narrator.device 37.7 and translator.library

@endnode

@node Installation "Notes on Installation"

You may install or update EO by double-clicking on the relevant install icon in the 'Instal' drawer located in the Everday Organiser archive (you will need the standard Installer program).

	@{b}What Occurs During Installation.@{ub}

Most of the EverydayOrganiser draw will be copied to a drawer of your choice that will later be assigned as 'Everyday:'

The installer will copy all the EO program documentation files to the Everyday:docs/<language> drawer. You should leave them there if you want on-line help.

The everyday.library (68000, 68020 or 68020+FPU) will be installed into your LIBS: directory.

Mark Thomas' TextField.gadget class will be installed into your 'SYS:classes/gadgets/" drawer.

You may be asked by the Installer whether you wish Alarmist to be copied into your WBStartup drawer. This is because Alarmist is required to act as a commodity and be present at all times. It doesn't make much sense to put it anywhere else.

A file called "Talk_Defaults" will be copied to your "S:" directory. It is an optional file used by the program "Talk" located in the Extras drawer. Consult the Talk documentation to find out more on this file.

After installation you'll probably end up with duplicates of some of the programs because there were copied from the installed drawer to other places like C:. The actual location of all the individual programs is not important, so you may reorganise things to how you like them best. Just remember to read the program docs to find out other relevant files.

The installer will make the assign "Everyday:" to the EverydayOrganiser drawer.

If you want to do the installation by hand then just drag the EO sub-drawer onto your HD. Make sure you copy the LIBS: drawer over to the correct place too! Within the Extras drawer you should copy Talk, Sam and Coder to C: and TimePrefs to your Preferences drawer. Finally if you install by hand, you are going to need to add the "Everyday:" assign to your S:User-Startup for the EverydayOrganiser drawer and copy the catalogs to their respective locale drawers. Then make yourself a coffee and read the docs.

EO release 2.30 contains some external custom class library files. These reside in the 'Everyday:mui' drawer. These files are not PUBLIC classes. This means that they should NOT, under any circumstances, be copied into the 'MUI:libs' drawer.

This document "Introduction.guide" should reside in the "Everyday:" drawer at all times.
@endnode

@node ImportingExporting "Importing and Exporting"

	@{b}IMPORTING AND EXPORTING@{ub}

· @{b}Locate@{ub}
   Locate contains import facilities. You may export data via the Print Data function using "Columns" which separate the fields with TABS. See program documentation for further explanation.

· @{b}Alarmist and On-Time@{ub}
   These programs contain no direct importing or exporting functions. This was left out because any importing and exporting functions would be too program specific and not very useful or flexible. BUT, and I repeat BUT (several million times 8) you may use the program's ARexx interface to accomplish the same thing and tailor the output/input your own situation. For example you may have a personal electronic organiser that interfaces with the computer. I have no such system (no money - unemployed) but you could transfer data using an ARexx script. The programs (including Locate) have the two ARexx commands GetField and SetField which you can use to transfer data between EO and your electronic organiser. This way the data would be transferred in the correct manner. It would be impossible to build a function into the programs that did this for all organisers on the market (unless there is a standard -  which I wouldn't be aware of). As usual, the good old Amiga come to the rescue again with ARexx.
@endnode

@node Languages "Languages"

	@{b}LANGUAGE IMPLIMENTATION@{ub}

As of version 2.00 (EO), all MUI programs have been completely cataloged. As of release 2.30, no catalogs are supplied with the intial distribution archive. However, the required translation material is supplied in the archive in the drawer "Translation."

If you wish to translate EO into your own language then please read the instructions provided in the above-mentioned drawer.

When you run On-Time in a supported language other than English you'll notice that some of the user-configurable strings are still in English, e.g. Custom Filter strings. This is because all the global settings (except Events, Tasks and Notes) are saved to the program's icon. You can of course alter these strings to your own language in the Configuration.
@endnode 

@node GettingStarted "Getting Started"

	@{b}GETTING STARTED@{ub}

Once you have installed Everyday Organiser, you can proceed to configure the program environments to your own tastes and start entering data.

You will find the program Alarmist has been copied into your 'SYS:WBStartup/' drawer. Therefore Alarmist will be running at all times. Later on you can decide whether to put On-Time into the same drawer if you have the extra memory and desire to do so.

It's probably a good idea to read the program documentation of On-Time and Alarmist at this stage. You will learn how to enter events into On-Time and how Alarmist will deal with them on a day-by-day basis.
@endnode

@node Compilation "Compilation Details"

	@{b}COMPILATION DETAILS@{ub}

Everyday Organiser was compiled using the SAS/C Development System version 6.57

The programs were compiled with the following options:

- String Merge
- Standard Maths
- All CPUs
- Parameters passed on registers
- No Stack Checking
- Inline calls to ROM Utility.Library

All programs were compiled with optimisation options:

- Global Optimiser on
- Peephole Optimiser on
- Instruction Scheduler on
- Loop Optimisation on
- Optimisation for Time not Size

My brain was compiled with a crowbar and a sledgehammer with no optimisation ;-)
@endnode

@node Thoughts

	@{b}I Can't Take This Sort of Thing Any Longer!!!@{ub}

In all the MUI programs I have seen coming out, there seems to be some lack of consistency in interface design. I would like to make a few suggestions. These are only my personal opinions and @{i}not necessarily@{ui} the opinions of others including Stefan Stuntz.

I want to address one point in particular that is driving me crazy!

· Wherever there is an instance of a gadget that has an associated label alongside of it, I would like to see them both enclosed in a Group Frame and placed on a Group Background. My reasoning for this is that often users have complicated window backgrounds and text put straight on top can be unreadable. If you place all your labeled objects on a Group Background WITH a Group Frame then the user can select an appropriate Group backdrop to increase readability. There will be instances when this is silly or unavoidable (but not many!!!!!!). 

I feel programmers should be more careful with the type of frame and background they choose. Thinking twice before selecting a frame will aid in maintaining a consistent look for all applications. I have seen instances where sets of Text Objects were grouped together in a Text Frame containing a Window Background. This doesn't make much sense to me at all. In such case, the programmer might want a Text Frame but surely he should use a Text Background if they are all text objects. Another example is a radio gadget smacked straight on top of a Window Background - very hard to read the labels indeed! A Group Frame and Group Background would clear this situation up. To tell you the truth, I'm getting rather sick of it! I begin to wonder whether programmers are actually using window backdrops or are they just using plain grey?

I really think that it's time for a MUI Style Guide that should be distributed with the developer documentation. This should indicate conventions when designing the layout of windows. This consistency thing really needs to be cleaned up! At the moment it is impossible to use even slightIy complex MUI WIndow Backdrops because most applications are putting text right on top of them.

I believe that Group Frames and Group Backgrounds should be used more often (within reason). In 99% of occasions, labeled objects should NEVER stand alone directly on a Window Background. I feel that labeled gadgets should almost always appear on a Group Background. I use the following definition when I want to enclose or group together a set of objects.

#define MyGroupFrame     GroupFrame,     MUIA_Background, MUII_GroupBack
#define MyGroupFrameT(s) GroupFrameT(s), MUIA_Background, MUII_GroupBack

For example:
...
Child, VGroup, MyGroupFrame,
   Child, ColGroup(2),
      Child, Label2("Easy to read because the user"),
      Child, String("", 10),
      Child, Label1("can set an uncomplicated Group Background"),
      Child, CheckMark(0),
   End,
End
...

This ends my major gripe with programmers that use MUI. I don't think I recall one single MUI program where I haven't found a labeled gadget straight on top of a Window Background.

· Menu layout on the Amiga is almost a case of pot-luck sometimes. Other OS platforms have rigid layout rules. Running through menus to find a particular item can be a real pain sometimes. I believe that Starting with Project, Edit and Settings Menus is a good basis for logical menu layout. Throwing everything in the Project menu can be very confusing as well.

If you have any criticisms of the layout in my programs then please email me!
@endnode

@node TheAuthor

	@{b}ABOUT THE AUTHOR@{ub}

The Everyday Organiser system was written (and copyrighted) by Mathew Wilson using an Amiga 2000 with 18 Megabytes of memory, GVP 33MHz-030/Series II SCSI, OS 3.1,  the SAS/C Development System (6.57), lots of paper and asprin.

After the Purchase of an IBM based PC, EO release 2.30 was never planned to happen. After much  frustration with the PC, I returned to the Amiga to 'see what happens.' It is also because of the feedback I received from people that made new EO releases possible.

This project has taken a considerable amount of time and energy. I maintain it as @{"Giftware" link Giftware} in some distant hope that it might help the Amiga in some small way. If you like Everyday Organiser then why not send me a donation, postcard or email me?

If you are an artist and would like to make some icons for EO then please send them to me for possible inclusion in the next release!

You may contact me (or send postcards) at:

	Box 6022, Halifax Street
	Adelaide SA, 5000
	AUSTRALIA

	EMail: mind@inorbit.com
	WWW:   http:www.adam.com.au/~mwilson/
@endnode

